place.name: ASLACTON
place.gazetteerText: ASLACTON, a parish in Depwade district, Norfolk; on an affluent of the river Yare, 1½ mile W of Forncett r. station, and 6 ENE of New Buckenham. Post Town, Forncett under Long Stratton. Acres, 1,194. Real property, £2,300. Pop., 356. Houses, 76. The property is much subdivided. The manor belonged to the Le Neves; and was the native place of Sir William le Neve, the herald and antiquary in the time of Charles I. The living is a p. curacy in the diocese of Norwich. Value, £58. Patron, the Rev. T. G. Curtler. The church is good; and there are a Wesleyan chapel and 18 acres of fuel allotment. (In 1870-72, John Marius Wilson's Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales)
